---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro'
import Nav from '../components/sections/Nav.astro'
import Footer from '../components/sections/Footer.astro'

// DRAFT. The developer agreement portion is a starting point and is NOT yet in
// effect; it needs legal review and a named contracting entity before paid
// third-party plugins are enabled. The user-facing portion describes how the
// marketplace works today. See
// docs/explorations/0215_[_]_TERMS_AND_PRIVACY_REFRESH_FOR_CLOUD_AI_AND_MARKETPLACE.md
const updated = 'June 24, 2026'
---

<Base title="Marketplace Terms - xNet" description="Terms for installing and publishing plugins in the xNet marketplace.">
  <Nav />

  <main class="min-h-screen bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
    <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16 lg:py-24">
      <header class="mb-8">
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-white mb-4">Marketplace Terms</h1>
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300">
          For people who install plugins, and for developers who publish them.
        </p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-4">Last updated: {updated}</p>
      </header>

      <article class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none prose-headings:font-semibold prose-a:text-blue-600 dark:prose-a:text-blue-400">

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>For everyone</h2>
          <p>
            The <a href="/plugins">xNet marketplace</a> lets you discover and install plugins that extend the
            app. Some plugins are built by the xNet project ("first-party"); many are built by third parties
            ("community plugins"). These Marketplace Terms are part of our <a href="/terms">Terms of
            Service</a>.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>For people installing plugins</h2>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>Community plugins are third-party software.</strong> They are provided by their
              authors, not by xNet. We don't warrant them and aren't responsible for what they do.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>You grant capabilities.</strong> Before install, the app shows the capabilities a
              plugin requests — which of your data it can read or write, which hosts it may reach, and any
              host APIs it uses — and asks for your consent. Grant only what you're comfortable with.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Plugins run in a sandbox.</strong> Community plugins run with only the capabilities you
              grant. Still, treat a plugin like any third-party software: install ones you trust.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Your data.</strong> What a plugin does with data you grant it is governed by that
              plugin's author and their own privacy terms, not ours.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Paid plugins.</strong> If a plugin charges, the price, billing model, and any trial are
              shown before you buy. Purchases may be processed by xNet (via Stripe) or by the author directly,
              as indicated. Refunds for author-billed plugins are the author's responsibility.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Removal.</strong> We may delist or disable a plugin that violates these terms or our
              <a href="/acceptable-use">Acceptable Use Policy</a>, or that is reported as harmful.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>For developers publishing plugins</h2>
          <div class="not-prose mb-6 rounded-lg border border-amber-300 bg-amber-50 p-4 text-sm text-amber-900 dark:border-amber-500/40 dark:bg-amber-500/10 dark:text-amber-200">
            <strong>Draft developer agreement — not yet in effect.</strong> The paid-plugin terms below are a
            working draft pending legal review and a named contracting entity. Paid third-party plugins are
            not enabled until this is finalized. To publish or sell early, contact
            <a href="mailto:legal@xnet.fyi" class="underline">legal@xnet.fyi</a>.
          </div>
          <p>By submitting a plugin to the marketplace, you agree that:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <strong>You have the rights</strong> to publish the plugin and license it under one of the
              accepted licenses (an OSI license or the Functional Source License), and your plugin and its
              metadata don't infringe others' rights.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>You accurately declare capabilities.</strong> Your manifest must request only the
              capabilities your plugin actually needs and describe them honestly.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Provided "as is."</strong> Your plugin is offered to users without warranty from xNet.
              xNet is a distributor and is not a party to the relationship between you and your users beyond
              what's described here.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Your own privacy obligations.</strong> If your plugin processes or stores user data
              outside the user's own data, you must publish and follow a privacy policy that meets applicable
              law, and you must have any permissions needed to share data with third parties.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Prohibited content and behavior.</strong> No malware, data exfiltration, deceptive
              capability requests, or content that violates our <a href="/acceptable-use">Acceptable Use
              Policy</a>.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Payments and revenue share.</strong> For plugins billed through xNet, we collect a
              platform fee (currently 10% of the sale) and remit the rest to you; you're responsible for your
              taxes. You may instead use your own checkout ("bring your own billing"), in which case you set
              and handle pricing, refunds, and support directly.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Support and updates.</strong> You're responsible for supporting your plugin and for the
              security of your updates.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Indemnity.</strong> To the extent permitted by law, you'll indemnify and hold harmless
              xNet and its maintainers from claims arising out of your plugin, your content, or your breach of
              these terms.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Takedown and revocation.</strong> We may remove, delist, or revoke a plugin that
              violates these terms, is reported as harmful, or poses a security risk — those grounds, and
              not others. We maintain a revocation mechanism so that delisted plugins can be disabled in
              the app.
            </li>
            <li>
              <strong>Ranking neutrality.</strong> Plugins published by xNet or its maintainers receive no
              ranking, placement, or search preference over anyone else's. We rank on the same signals for
              everyone, we don't sell placement, and choosing bring-your-own-billing over xNet billing does
              not affect where your plugin appears. The catalog and install path are MIT-licensed, so you
              can also run your own marketplace and skip us entirely.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="mb-12">
          <h2>Changes and contact</h2>
          <p>
            We may update these terms as the marketplace evolves. We'll update the date above and, for
            significant changes, post a notice. Questions: <a href="mailto:legal@xnet.fyi">legal@xnet.fyi</a>.
            See also our <a href="/terms">Terms of Service</a> and <a href="/privacy">Privacy Policy</a>.
          </p>
        </section>

      </article>
    </div>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Base>
